This is not bait.
If I were Red_Nine and wanted to salvage Anon's relationship with Annie, I would rewrite chapter 8. It's unacceptable in its current form.
The dream sequence at the beginning is fine. I would start by making Anon less withdrawn and more openly hostile. This change makes sense because he's trapped with his abuser. He feels like a cornered animal, so he can't afford to be meek. When he realizes she has the gun, he stops any physical threats, but switches to verbal abuse. He goes on a whole rant about how the Redecker was right, and that you can never trust a mutt.
Annie not understanding what she did wrong at first is fine, but when she realizes the depths of his shell-shock, she shuts up. She has a full on mental breakdown when she actually understands that she raped him. And Anon doesn't pussyfoot around it, either. He tells her "you raped me," in those exact words, because she handcuffed him to a bed and drugged him to make it happen. She should have known better.
He doesn't care about her emotional state, and wants to escape the building, but realizes he's still too physically hurt to leave, so he bides his time. The "Stolen Gun" scene stays intact for the most part, with him stealing the gun when she gets to close but stopping short of killing her. This is when he decides instead to run for the door, opening it before she calls out to him to stop. He makes a comment about her fixation with him, and she yells that she doesn't want him to kill himself walking into the blizzard. He closes the door but tells her that he's leaving when the weather clears. As the night goes on, it gets colder, so he approaches her and tells her they need to sleep back to back to conserve warmth. He tells her that if he catches her touching him below his waist in his sleep he'll kill her. She agrees, hoping to regain the trust she violated. He hears her crying out in her sleep for him not to leave.
Now they have room to rebuild rapport in chapter 9.

Welcome to Nuevo Carcangel, circa 2174. A century has passed since a plague killed half of humanity. No one living now knows why some of the survivors are called chimeras, nor how the plague created them - if it did.
Christina Marlowe, a private investigator and a fox-type chimera, has other concerns. She's living in one of the biggest city-states. What technology used to exist is gone. She knows the trains and streetcars, her trusty revolver, and that she needs a big case.

Anonymous Tue 30 Aug 2022 02:21:15 No.50545770 Report
Quoted By: >>50545875
>>50545062
You should just start drawing. Most people don't draw because they want to be able to instantly turn what's in their head into what's on the paper. No one can do this right off the bat. You need to let go, acknowledge that you're a beginner and allow yourself to make beginner work. Beyond that there's two main components to develop, motor skill and technical knowledge. Motor skill is literally your ability to make clear, intentioned, marks on your paper or tablet. That skill will develop as you draw and you can do targeted practice if you're not confident in your ability to make those marks with confidence. Technical skill is the other half and basically involves all the sorts of knowledge that you need to accurately draw the things you want to. Things like knowledge of anatomy, of perspective, of lighting, ect.
The very beginning of both of those branches is drawing. Acknowledge that what you make is not going to be perfect and do it anyways because that's the only way you'll get better.

Anonymous Tue 30 Aug 2022 03:36:39 No.50547245 Report
Quoted By: >>50547544 >>50550892
>>50545062
You need to look at it this way: To get good at drawing, you need to draw many things. The biggest factor preventing you from accomplishing this is your own inability to form the habit.
To form the habit of spending 30-60 minutes sketching, do the following:
>1. Make the cue as obvious as possible
Take sketchbook out of your goddamn closet! Stop putting it in drawers, don’t put books on top of it. Leave it within an arms length, and keep your pencils sharp and handy.
>2. Make the response easy and painless.
When you see your sketchbook, be inspired! Think of some basic poses you might want to try out. At the same time, admit that your work is going to look like shit. You NEED it to look like shit so you begin to understand what works and what doesn't. Fear no mistake. It's okay to finish a drawing with mistakes. Success is a mountain of failures with a cherry on top. Even a shitty sketch builds the mountain. Try not to miss days. A 5min sketch is far better than nothing.
>3. Make the reward great
Post about it in thread! Show your furry friends, they'll always support you. It'll make you feel like you've done something. Don’t get discouraged by negative comments, those people don’t know shit about your journey. Focus on your progress. Did you Pay more attention to certain body parts this time? Great!
4. HAVE FUN!
I'm not kidding. You need to draw what gives you joy. It's the only way to maintain the habit. It's going to be uncomfortable at first. But deep in your heart you'll know it gives you pleasure. It's like a seed that grows every time you draw something. You need to know that it's a positive experience through and through.

Pic related is my 28th drawing. I always draw one or two things a day, even if it's a scribble. The threads' greatest artists have given me good drawing tips, and I wouldn't be here without them. Now let's get to it!

I know I'm late to the party and lots of other anons have already offered plenty of good advice, like >>50547245, but really I can only boil it down to three things:

1) Accept that you're gonna suck.
2) Always draw from reference.
3) Learn the fundamentals while drawing things that make you happy.

That's it really. I'm not a very good authority on what it takes to be a good artist judging by the abilities of some of the other artists in this thread, but I like to think that I've made an improvement over the years. And if I can do it, you can too. Picrel, the right is the first drawin' I ever felt comfortable putting my dumbfuck signature on, two whole years ago. The left is something I posted in the thread a few days ago. Not the most impressive improvement, but I'm happy with how far along I've progressed, and I know I still have a long way to go.
Best of luck anon, and don't be afraid to ask for help if you feel confused.

Perhaps I should have elaborated more on what I consider a reference. Composition, colors, linework, lighting, posing, and form can all be their own separate references for a single piece. You will certainly reach a point where you can draw from imagination, but if you want to improve as an artist you should still continue to use reference to guide your creative process. References are one of the best teaching tools out there for artists and thinking you're beyond using them alongside developing a "style" too early are one of the biggest pitfalls out there that cause new artists to stagnate.
